In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = new Window(new AppShell());

        window.Created  += (s, e) => Log("Created");
        window.Activated   += (s, e) => Log("Activated");
        window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Log("Deactivated");
        window.Stopped     += (s, e) => Log("Stopped");
        window.Resumed     += (s, e) => Log("Resumed");
        window.Destroying  += (s, e) => Log("Destroying");

        // Visibility events (mobile)
        window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Log("Backgrounding");

        return window;
    }

    static void Log(string evt)
        => System.Diagnostics.Debug.WriteLine($"[Window] {evt} @ {DateTime.Now:T}");
}
```

### Typical transition order

| Scenario | Event sequence |
|---|---|
| **App launch** | `Created → Activated` |
| **Switch away** | `Deactivated → Stopped` |
| **Switch back** | `Resumed → Activated` |
| **Close / kill** | `Destroying` |
| **iOS/Android background** | `Backgrounding` |

### Notes
- **`Backgrounding`** gives you a `BackgroundingEventArgs` with a `State` dictionary you can use to persist data before the OS may reclaim the process.
- All events fire on the **UI thread**, so keep handlers fast—write to `Debug.WriteLine` or queue to a background logger.
- On **desktop** (Windows/macOS), `Stopped`/`Resumed` map to minimize/restore.
